commentBody:
@Ash
I thought it was a very hard Friday!  Goes to show that we all know different things.






Emu food.

@Bill in Yokohama


Based on my solve time this should have been an extra-hard Saturday!

Your mileage may vary.....

@B 

You folks are a mystery.  If a majority find something easy, then it's easy.  That's not "subjective" any longer - it's a consensus!  Geez guys.  However, your point that finishers would obviously post first is very valid.  Only a later summarization or poll would tell the tale.

Doesn't the daily Connections have exactly the difficulty rating you seem to think is impossible to achieve?

@Bill 
Just a side comment....  I remember when VELCRO was very new and VERY expensive, but it was revolutionizing things for children with CP or other handicapping conditions that made ADLs diffiicult.
By the time I had my own children, it was everywhere.  When we needed lace-up shoes to go with our daughter's bracing, it was difficult to find (circa 1985 or so)....

@KLC 
It was a happy day for me when the BRER Rabbit and BRER Bear stories were recognized as being part of the African story-telling tradition (after some years of being banned.)  We kids were born in 'briarpatch' country...
I got it off the B, and I still don't know why.

@Bill 
Actually, (she "SHESPLAINED") a 'bluestocking' was just a scholarly or bookish younng woman--and it was meant in a somewhat derogatory sense.  As my mother told me --more than once--boys don't like girls who are smarter than they are and who beat them at games.  
I also wore glasses.

@Bill 
I was leaning towards your last meaning, but it's not limited to smut. I used to have to drive across the border to Maryland to buy booze on Sunday, because Delaware still had a "blue law" on the books. So it's any kind of moral pulchritude.

Go Bucks, Beat Blue!

@Linda Jo 
You are so right.  We are such gluttons for 
pun-ishment!  Have a great weekend.

@Mean Old Lady 

Loved your comment!  I coming around to the idea that you're not all that mean.

I'd never try haggis either.  And yet I love hot dogs and sausage.  I bet they're not all that different.

@Linda 

The fact that there were emojis didn't even register, since I got the answer via the verbal clue and a few crosses.

Of course, it's obvious they are there if you look for more than a microsecond, but as you said, they weren't necessary.

@Linda et al
What are you talking about????

I print the puzzle and solve with my pen, and there were no special effects on the grid when I clicked on Print....

@HeathieJ 

I have the same problem with emojis.  In some instances they can't be made larger by enlarging the screen.  

I so far have refused to use a magnifying glass with my computer.

@B 
Q: "Why give them such huge gusts of oxygen?". 
A: For the same reason porn is a multibillion dollar industry?

@Michael 

Ha!  

Congratulations!  Don't let anyone tell you it was too easy.
